autolisp-test-results-corrupted-to-t — pin the root cause behind rurban's report-generation workaround (engine dynamic-binding bug vs harness or-pattern)
===========================================================================================================================================================

Context: GitHub PR #5/#6 (Reini Urban, 2026-06-17/18, merged 2026-07-23)
worked around a crash in the conformance corpus's report generation:
after test execution, `results` / `descriptor` arrived as `T` inside
matrix / write-sexp-report / print-recap:

  [autolisp-test] no expectations file at: .../expectations/CLAUTOLISP/0.x/unknown.lsp
  [autolisp-test] matrix raised: FOREACH list argument must evaluate to a proper list, got T.
  [autolisp-test] write-sexp-report raised: FOREACH list argument must evaluate to a proper list, got T.
  [autolisp-test] print-recap raised: LENGTH expects a proper list, got T.

Reproduced on master (clautolisp 1.5.1) on 2026-07-23 immediately
before merging the workaround; gone after. The workaround
(autolisp-test/harness/run.lsp autolisp-test--guarded-apply +
`listp` guard + parameter renames in profiles.lsp / report.lsp) makes
the harness robust, but the PR calls the underlying behaviour a
"clautolisp dynamic-binding bug" and that claim is neither confirmed
nor refuted — this issue is the investigation.

What we know (probed 2026-07-23 on 1.5.1, --no-init):

  1. Core dynamic scoping is CORRECT:
       (setq v 'global)
       (defun callee ( / ) v)
       (defun caller ( / v) (setq v 'local) (callee))
       (caller)  =>  LOCAL                          ; ok
  2. Constructed list-lambdas see the caller's locals too:
       (defun caller2 ( / v) (setq v 'local2)
         (vl-catch-all-apply (list 'lambda nil 'v) nil))
       (caller2) =>  LOCAL2                         ; ok
  3. So the simple engine-bug hypothesis does not reproduce in
     isolation. Yet pre-workaround report generation DID receive T.

Prime suspect (harness logic, not the engine): the old run.lsp step-2
pattern

  (setq results (or (autolisp-test--guarded "apply-expectations"
                      (list 'lambda nil (list 'autolisp-test-apply-expectations
                                              'results 'overlay)))
                    results))

lets ANY non-nil non-list return value of apply-expectations (or of
the missing-expectations path — note the "no expectations file"
message right before the corruption; princ returns its argument)
overwrite `results` with T, which then flows into matrix /
write-sexp-report / print-recap. That is exactly the hole the PR's
`listp` guard closes, and it requires no engine misbehaviour at all.

To do:

  - Check out the pre-workaround harness (parent of the 2026-07-23
    merge of PR commits, harness at 8207b6d state), instrument step 2
    of autolisp-test-run-all, and capture WHAT returned T and WHY
    (expected: autolisp-test-load-expectations /
    autolisp-test-apply-expectations return path on the
    missing-expectations branch).
  - If it is purely the or-pattern: close this issue recording that
    the "dynamic-binding bug" label was a misdiagnosis, that the
    engine is exonerated (probes 1-2 above), and that the workaround
    is simply better harness code — then also fix
    autolisp-test-apply-expectations to return a list on every path,
    so the guard never fires.
  - If a test file's global (setq results ...) DOES leak through a
    binding boundary somewhere (e.g. through vl-catch-all-apply's
    argument evaluation, or usubr locals under the debugger
    instrumentation fork): minimal repro, then fix in the engine, and
    add a conformance test pinning AutoLISP dynamic-scoping semantics
    (caller locals visible in callees and in constructed lambdas).
  - Either way: the expectations path prints "unknown.lsp" because
    the descriptor's version field is unknown under --no-init; check
    whether that fallback is intended.
